TCL - Arrays:
    An array is a systematic arrangement of a group of elements using indices.
Syntax:
    set ArrayName(Index) value
Example:
    set PD_Topic(1) Floorplan
    set PD_Topic(2) Powerplan
    set PD_Topic(3) Placement
    puts $PD_Topic(1)
    puts $PD_Topic(2)
    puts $PD_Topic(3)
    
Build in function of arrays:
    1. Array Size
    2. Array Iteration
    3. Associative Arrays
    4. Array indices
    5. Iteration of Associative arrays
    
1. size of arrays:
syntax:
    [array size variablename]
Example:
    set PD_Topic(0) Floorplan
    set PD_Topic(1) Powerplan
    puts [array size PD_Topic]
    
2. Array iteration:
    Though, array indices can be non-continuous like values specified for index 1 then index 10 and so on. 
    But, in case they are continuous, we can use array iteration to access elements of the array.
Example:
      set PD_Topic(0) Floorplan
      set PD_Topic(1) Powerplan
      for { set index 0 } { $index < [array size PD_Topic] } { incr index } {
       puts "PD_Topic($index) : $PD_Topic($index)"
      }

3. Associative Arrays:
    Arrays are stored and retrieved without any specific order. Associative arrays have an index that is not necessarily a number, and can be sparsely populated.
Example:
      set personA(Name) "Ajaykumar"
      set personA(Age) 24
      puts $personA(Name)
      puts $personA(Age)

4. Indices of Array:
syntax:
      [array names variablename]
Example:
      set personA(Name) "Ajaykumar"
      set personA(Age) 24
      puts [array names personA]

5. Iteration of Associative arrays
Example:
       set personA(Name) "Ajaykumar"
       set personA(Age) 24
       foreach index [array names personA] {
       puts "personA($index): $personA($index)"
      }


Example 1:

        array set numbers { 1 10 2 20 3 30}
        set first_number $numbers(1)
        puts $first_number
        set second_number $numbers(2)
        puts $second_number
        set third_number $numbers(3)
        puts $third_number




      
